name: Castle Combe - Spring Action Day
description:
Image source: Thomas Page (https://www.meetup.com/Bristol-Photography-Group/members/8264917/) (Japfest 2012)

Castle Combe - Spring Action Day - Saturday 8th April
Castle Combe race track is located about 20 miles from Bristol and is a popular racing venue. The Spring Action day is the official start to the performance racing car season at Castle Coombe. It is an action packed day.

Spring Action Day info (Castle Combe website) (https://castlecombecircuit.co.uk/shows/spring-action-day/8/4/2017/)

Ticket prices:
Adult/Senior: £15/£10

Suggested Equipment:
Tripod (optional)
Suitable Clothing if chilly!
Picnic (food prices at the track can be pricey)

Map of location: Castle Combe Race Track (https://www.google.co.uk/maps/place/Castle+Combe+Circuit/@51.4935115,-2.2200388,17z/data=%213m1%214b1%214m5%213m4%211s0x487179fc19542e41:0xfdd9ccaedb930702%218m2%213d51.4935115%214d-2.2178501)
(Address: Castle Combe Race Track, Castle Combe, Wiltshire, SN14 7EY)
(Google Maps location not 100% accurate)

Getting there
By Car
The Castle Combe Circuit is 5 miles west of Chippenham on the B4039, just half a mile from the village of Castle Combe.

By Rail
Chippenham is on the main line from Paddington to Bristol Temple Meads. For travel enquiries, contact National Rail enquiries on 0845 7484950. Taxis are available at the station. One of the main taxi companies operating in Chippenham is Ezy's Taxis. They are contactable on 01249 650088.

By Helicopter
Castle Combe Circuit is situated 45 minutes from Bristol Airport and 90 minutes from Heathrow. Helicopter landing strictly by prior permission only (PPO). A landing fee is required. Contact the Castle Combe Circuit office for further details on 01249 782929.

By Tardis/DeLorean DMC-12
Tardis - you may arrive in the wrong era
DeLorean DMC-12 - Must travel at 88mph!

Map of Castle Combe Race Track
how_to_find_us: Meet in the Quarry car park (see map in event description)

name: Challenge | Bristol
description:
Location information: http://www.coffee1.co.uk/our-locations/welsh-back/

For the 3rd challenge of the year we're heading to the Welsh Back/Redcliffe area of Bristol. From here it's just a short walk to the harbourside, Temple Meads, Broadmead, Bedminster and Park Street.

As usual the challenge involves:

5 topics / 2 hours.  You can use any camera you like - mobile phone, iPad, DSLR, film, compact. The challenge is to capture something as interesting and unique as possible.  That could be, for example, an alternative angle, a different perspective or viewpoint, a close up, vibrant colour or unusual detail. Be creative.

1.  Themes will be given out on the day by your event hosts at 11am and posted on the meetup site at this time

2.  You have up to 2 hours to photograph the themes, shooting as many different versions and options as you like

3.  Upload 5 final images : 1 for each theme only - feel free to put the rest on our Flickr site so everyone can see more of your work

4.  Take time to look and comment on other members' images - and let them know what you like about their shot(s)

name: Springtime Bluebell Walk
description:
Image source: avonwildlifetrust website

Prior's Wood was once part of the Tyntesfield Estate, this wildlife-rich nature reserve has ancient woodland, streams and plantations. Parts of Prior's Wood date back to the 1600s, and are very close to the type of woodland that developed after the last Ice Age about 10,000 years ago. In spring, the bluebell displays are some of the best in the region.

Map location of Prior's Wood can be found here --> Prior's Wood
(Address: Caswell Lane. Portbury, Bristol, BS20 7UF)
(Google Maps location not 100% accurate)


Parking: Parking is limited. There is a lay-by on the Clapton-in-Gordano road, park on the right just after passing the last house in Portbury village.

Suggested Equipment:
Tripod (optional)
Suitable Clothing if chilly!
Suitable footwear


More info: Prior's Wood

Re: Uploading photos

- Please can you upload a maximum of 4 photos ONLY, if you have more please put them on Flickr, there is limited space on Meetup

<a href="http://www.avonwildlifetrust.org.uk/reserves/priors-wood"></a>
